abstract = {Objectives
Oral medicine, due to its interfaces with medicine, is a central specialty for the progress of dentistry in developing countries and has undergone a clear expansion in several parts of the globe in addition to the United States, the UK, and Europe. Hence, it has become paramount to define the status of the clinical practice of Oral Medicine in Latin American and Caribbean countries so that the results may drive consolidation and practice progress. Methods: this was a cross-sectional study using a self-administered REDCap web-based survey designed by an international panel of Oral Medicine experts (in Spanish and English) to assess the current state of Oral Medicine practice in Latin America and the Caribbean. The survey was sent to Oral Medicine specialists and responses were analyzed using descriptive statistics.
Results
Specialists representing 21 countries answered the questionnaire showing a mean age of 46.9 years and a slight male predominance (1.1:1). A high rate (over 90%) of training based on postgraduate courses coupled with >75% of the specialists having training in international institutions was observed. Oral medicine is recognized as an official specialty (certified by ministries of health or education) in approximately 40% of the countries targeted by the study; in more than 66% of the countries it is independent of oral pathology and more than 42% of countries reported official graduate programs in oral medicine. Approximately 50% of the countries studied do not have policies or regulations for professionalization in oral medicine and a very heterogeneous understanding of the clinical competencies of oral medicine was observed. Private practice was the most common field of work in the investigated context and more than 90% of the specialists representing Latin America and the Caribbean reported that the lack of recognition of oral medicine as a specialty by multidisciplinary health teams is the greatest barrier to the expansion of specialized clinical practice.
Conclusions
This seems to be the first study to depicture the professional profile of Latin American and Caribbean oral medicinists and to demonstrate a heterogenous professional background as well as a poorly recognized reputation within a multidisciplinary medical context.}
